Among the six “sandalwood oils” tested, none of them met the requirements of ISO 3518:2002 concerning the content of the main component (α-santanol). By assessing the chromatographic profile (chemical composition) of the samples, it can be concluded that:
Only one oil (P6) turned out to be the genuine sandalwood oil— Santalum album, and the description corresponded to the information provided by the manufacturer;
Three samples (P1, P2 and P3) were obtained from Amyris balsamifera; two manufacturers provided correct information (P1 and P2) about its origin, while the third incorrectly claimed it to be Santalum album;
Two oils (P4 and P5) were synthetic mixtures, which were supposed to imitate sandalwood fragrance. While P4 was labeled as being obtained from Santalum album, it turned out to be a mixture of chemical substances synthesized under laboratory conditions. The manufacturer of P5 did not indicate any source of origin.
